n why I wanted me default compile to be<br />warning-clean. Of course, then gcc started adding more warnings, and<br />it's not clean any more ("warning: statement with no effect" from the<br />fact that we just define many functions to '(0)' when they are<br />disabled) but my current personal compile config only gets four<br />warnings.<br /><br />I realize there are *many* more warnings once you start enabling more<br />special code - as usual, the core code tends to be better quality, and<br />the further away from that base you get, the worse things get.<br /><br />But it would definitely be good if most kernel developers did the<br />above. Do it for just your personal config - at least you'll see the<br />warnings in code you write (because presumably your personal config<br />will have that code enabled ;)<br /><br />                    Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
